"Yes, sir. They should be on their way by now; we gave them time to pack food from the mess hall." At 05:00, Exodus platoon gathered at the vehicle yard. Captain肖 stood on a crate and began to speak.
"We are heading to the I-131 frontline operations base, 50 miles outside the city of Ianlos. We will support the ongoing siege operation and then attack Ianlos City to clear out the insurgents there. We will use this as a base to advance into the mountains," Captain肖 explained. "Take your squad and prepare to move out."
The platoon dispersed, with each squad, under the leadership of their squad leader, boarding a tank. Kollen climbed onto a tank at the front of the convoy and sat with Nimitz, Kress, and two new recruits. Kollen remembered they had arrived just a few days ago, but he didn't know much about them. He sat on the edge of the tank with his legs dangling, adjusting his backpack and radio equipment, connecting it to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey, Kollen, is Harris still keeping Snowball?" Nimitz asked after they had settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Kollen recalled the incident that morning when they had stolen the chicken from the farm. "Right, I'm sure of it."
Kollen looked toward another tank and saw Harris and his team. He glimpsed a chick peering around from behind Harris's backpack.
"Right, he's still keeping that chicken," Kollen replied. At that moment, the turret hatch of the tank clanged open, and the tank commander appeared before them.
"All tanks are moving out," the commander said calmly and clearly into his headset. The tanks of the armor platoon and the Skorch armored vehicles roared to life, beginning their advance. Kollen's Cronos tank released its brakes, moving forward and joining the formation. The tanks formed a wedge formation as they crossed the Itanía plain. The winter blizzard had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud still remained.
After about an hour, a new recruit (Kollen remembered his name was Olsen) spoke up, asking, "Lieutenant, have you been on the front lines since the war began?"
"Yes, since the Firestorm Operation," Kollen replied. "We thought the battle would be over in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"More than that," Nimitz joined the conversation. "Their weapons and numbers exceeded our expectations. They shot down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Dammit, we should have been able to see it on the road."
"Well, I will bravely fight for the Federation," Olsen said firmly, "I won't be scared off by those terrorists."
"You say that now, but from what I've seen, most of the newbies like you who just turned adults piss themselves at the sound of gunfire," Kress said.
"We'll see about that," Kollen said with a smile. Olsen said nothing more.
"Exodus Deputy Commander! Exodus Commander!" Kollen's radio equipment called out. "We have a heat signature 350 yards at 20 degrees to our right front."
Kollen climbed onto the tank and put on his optical goggles. After switching to thermal imaging mode, he saw the heat signature in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," Kollen said into his throat microphone.
"Are they enemies?" another recruit, Natalia, asked.
"Can't tell," Kollen said, opening his microphone. "Exodus platoon, don't fire unless attacked, first bring them out."
As they came closer, the faint heat signature, which was a blurry spot, became a clearer outline. One of them ran toward somewhere, picked up something, and then ran back to the small hill. Then, these people crouched down and took up firing positions.
"We've encountered the enemy!" Captain肖 shouted into his radio when orange tracer rounds were fired from the ridge. Bullets pinged against the side of the tank, and the assault team members jumped off the tanks and took cover behind them. An anti-tank missile screamed through the air and slammed into the ground behind the tank formation, shrapnel striking one of the tanks. Another missile hit the side of an APS-Cerberus Skorch armored vehicle and exploded. After the ammunition detonated, the vehicle's crew scrambled out, seeking cover.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 yards. Fire!" the tank platoon leader shouted into his radio. The main guns of Iron 1-2 and 1-3 fired, shells roaring toward the ridge, and the explosion sent dirt and debris flying into the air.
"Send out the sentry bots!" Knox shouted, observing the ridge with a telescope. The rear hatch of a "Hound" opened, and a soldier without a weapon stepped out, wearing a special headset. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two "Sentry" robots responded. Their slender metal arms and legs moved forward, running quickly. The robots were equipped with weapons, but they were all slung over their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Kress asked as he observed.
"Looks like we're capturing them alive," Kollen guessed, watching as the two sentry robots disappeared into the ash and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but soon died down. After a while, the two sentry robots returned, dragging a person with them, leaving a trail of footprints in the mud and snow. Upon reaching a safe area, the robots threw the prisoner to the ground, and he landed heavily in the mud and snow, groaning in pain.
He struggled to stand up, and Captain肖 approached. Captain肖 turned to one of the sentry robots. "How many were there?"
"Three dead, sir," the sentry robot replied. "The rest have fled on foot."
Captain肖 nodded and turned to Kollen and Kress, who were standing nearby. "You two, can you take this person away?"
